
Edited by Hector Neff 
Maya Zooarchaeology: New Directions in Method and Theory. KI TTY F. EMERY, editor. Cotsen Institute of Archaeology at UCLA, Monograph 51, 2004. 310 pp., illustrations, maps, index, $40.00 (paper). 
Reviewed by Laura L. Scheiber, Indiana University 
For some the term zooarchaeology conjures endless tables of animal taxa and specimen counts. The authors of Maya Zooarchaeology work to change this percep­tion by preparing a book that is primarily concerned with people and animals and human-animal interac­tions. Presented in sixteen chapters, the clear, concise contributions in this volume are interesting and highly accessible. The book is divided into six thematic cate­gories, including methods, animals and environment, significance of ancient species, Maya animals in ritual, politics, and economics, animal use in Maya border areas, and new perspectives. 
In the first chapter, Kitty Emery traces historical tra­jectories of the study of animal remains in the Maya area. Maya zooarchaeologists currently engage in a social zooarchaeology that moves beyond subsistence economy and environmental reconstructions to draw upon broader issues of social organization, political agendas, and ritual activities. Emery credits Mary Pohl, Elizabeth Wing, and Nancy Hamblin for their ground­breaking work with fauna! collections in the Maya area and for bringing anthropological questions to the fore­front of zooarchaeological research. She emphasizes the need for good comparative data between sites and regions and researchers. Without standardized methods for recovering fauna! remains and for reporting aggre­gate bone data, regional and temporal comparisons will remain elusive if not impossible. In a second chapter Emery reviews different methods for quantifying zooar­chaeological data, which often add up to tens of thou­sands of bone fragments in an area of high animal diversity and low preservation conditions. In the next 
chapter,Norbert Stanchly observes that taphonomic agents are too often minimized. Through procurement, processing, disposal, and post-depositional activities, bone assemblages are changed and rearranged, leading to potential bias in interpretation. Harriet Beaubien dis­cusses exotic marine materials found as funerary offer­ings in a royal tomb within Structure l OL-26 at Copan. Extremely careful methods to recover highly frag­mented materials in both the field and the lab allowed conservators to identify the remains of spiny oyster, stingray, and sponge, which suggests a relationship between elite mortuary practices and the watery realm of these invertebrates. 
In the section addressing animals and past environ­ments, GIS, stable isotopes, and standard specimen counts and weights are used to reconstruct past condi­tions. Using an innovative approach, Heather McKil­lop and Terance Winemiller conduct GIS spatial analysis of shell distribution at the Late Classic through Early Postclassic village at Frenchman's Cay, Belize, to show a changing "maritime landscape" based on shell habitats. Islanders relied on marine and freshwa­ter shellfish for food and manufactured ritual and domestic shell objects. Emery next explores the envi­ronment of collapse in the Petexbatun area of Guatemala. Fauna] taxa diversity and isotopic chemi­cal studies of deer bone from the sites of Dos Pi las and Aguateca, among others, suggest that an environmen­tal collapse did not cause a political collapse in this region. Instead, environmental stability is suggested during a time of social change. Marilyn Masson addresses variations in hunting, turtling, fishing, and farming, based on bone specimen counts (NISP) and weight data from four Preclassic to Postclassic period sites/communities in northern Belize, including Pull­trowser Swamp, Colha, Northern River Lagoon, and Laguna de On. Contrary to assumptions that agricul­tural products dominated the diet, Masson documents high animal diversity through time, with terrestrial 
