mammals and turtles comprising a large part of the fau­na! assemblage. The wide array of animal taxa suggests that numerous ecological resource zones were utilized through time and space. 
Ancient species are the focus of the next several chapters, with emphasis on freshwater mussels, deer, dogs, and marine fish. Although the widespread use of marine shellfish and freshwater snails is well docu­mented, freshwater pearly mussels were also used as food and for ritual purposes throughout the Maya area, as traced in a chapter by Terry Powis. Using stable iso­tope signatures, Christine White, Mary Pohl, Henry Schwarcz, and Fred Longstaffe study deer and dog diet from Late Preclassic though Late Classic contexts at Lagerto, Tikal, and Copan. They demonstrate that both deer and dogs were sometimes fed a high com diet. Because dogs are domesticated animals and scaveng­ing omnivores, we may expect a close relationship between humans and dogs. On the other hand, deer diet ranged from extensive browsing of wild plants to major consumption of com. Com in the deer diet indicates pur­poseful feeding by humans and practices of deer hus­bandry. Kevin Seymour concludes this section with an experimental study of the percentages of useable fish meat weight for 14 marine fish taxa. He concludes that while a figure of 90% of useable fish weight is gener­ally cited, the actual useable meat weight is probably much less. Using regression analysis, he calculates fish meat weight from individual fish bone elements from the Early Postclassic site of Marco Gonzalez in Belize. 
Animals in ritual, political, and economics are explored in the next section of the book. Two chapters address large scale spatial and temporal variation at the cities of Caracol in Belize and Tikal in Guatemala. Wendy Teeter examines the daily use of animals at Caracol from the Late Preclassic through the Terminal Classic. Although the population grew and social com­plexity increased through time, access to animal taxa in general and large mammal taxa in particular remained relatively stable. By studying the number and weight of fauna! remains from the site, Teeter reveals evidence of animal management through time, ceremonial use, and the presence of specialized bone workshops. Dif­ferent consumption patterns are also interpreted between outlying residents and urban elites. Focusing exclusively on non-domestic contexts, Hattula Moholy­Nagy analyzes distributions of tens of thousands of bone specimens from burials and caches at Tikal. Local and exotic animals and animal bone objects were com­monly and purposefully placed in elite mortuary and ceremonial contexts. This chapter adds to the author's recent summary of utilitarian objects in The Artifacts of Tikal (2002). 
Providing perspectives from the borders of the Maya area, Thomas Wake discusses the vertebrate fauna from a residential platform mound at the Early Formative site of Paso de la Amada in Chiapas, Mexico. In establish­ing a baseline for Pacific Coast archaeofaunal exploita­tion, Wake shows that fish, reptiles, and small mammals, especially those found near rivers and swamps, domi­nated the diet of these tropical agriculturalists. John Henderson and Rosemary Joyce address fauna! distri­butions from sites of the Lower Ulua Valley near the Caribbean coast of Honduras. Even a preliminary analy­sis of bones reveals a diversity of fauna in space and time, fitting well with the authors' characterization of decentralized political authority in the southeast Maya periphery. In a small but interesting part of this chap­ter, the authors reexamine William Duncan Strong's field notes and journal from 1936, in which he describes recovering turkey remains in a burial from the Early Postclassic site of Las Flores Bolsa. 
The book ends with two nicely written concluding chapters. David Pendergast provides an archaeologist's retrospective on Maya fauna! studies. While he applauds the fact that fauna! remains are now used to demonstrate evidence of past activities and not just diversity of taxa, he is also concerned that researchers do not adequately address serious flaws in understanding the nature of accumulation and dispersal of midden deposits. His chapter provides a cautionary tale/tail to remind zooar­chaeologists to pay close attention to context. The last chapter is written by Elizabeth Wing, who stresses the continued refinement of Maya zooarchaeology. Accord­ing to Wing, the most productive avenue of Maya zooar­chaeological research addresses issues of human ecology and domestication. Human control of animals led to their incorporation in sacred and political realms as food, feast, sacrifice, and trade objects. 
Maya Zooarchaeology presents a compelling case study of what animal bones can tell us about past rela­tionships between people and animals. It is a cohesive volume, consisting of thought-provoking, well-written chapters. Many of the authors grapple with extremely large sample sizes and try to connect animal remains to relevant issues and interpretations of the Maya past. The use of an exceptional base map throughout the book adds to the consistency of the volume, and an appendix of important species makes it easy to find ref­erences to particular animals. Scholars who want to know how animal bones can contribute information to their overall research questions should read this book. Researchers who are looking for good comparative data should consult this book. Instructors who want to draw attention to a strong regional case study of zooarchae­ology should assign this book. In many ways the book is an excellent companion to the volume edited by Christine White, Reconstructing Ancient Maya Diet 
